<h2 id="parsing-linear-transformation">Parsing Linear Transformation</h2>

<p>Transformation: A function that takes in an input vector and <em>moves</em> it.
Linear: The <em>movement</em> described above is linear if and only if</p>

<ol>
  <li>the origin remains</li>
  <li>lines stay as lines. (In other words, the set of vectors that have the same span remains the same after the transformation)</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="geometric-intuition-of-linear-transformation-in-matrix-multiplication">Geometric intuition of Linear Transformation in Matrix Multiplication</h2>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">T(\overrightarrow{v}) := A\overrightarrow{v}

This linear transformation _moves_ \$ \overrightarrow{v} \$ from the representation of the basis vectors in the coefficient matrix to the standard basis. (\$ \overrightarrow{e_x} = (1,0) \$, \$\overrightarrow{e_y} = (0, 1) \$ in \$ R_2 \$.)

An example in \$ R_2 \$ will make things clearer.

Recall the matrix multiplication operation</script>

<p>T(\overrightarrow{v}) :=
\begin{bmatrix}
i_1 &amp; j_1 <br />
i_2 &amp; j_2
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
v_1 <br />
v_2
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
i_1 <br />
i_2
\end{bmatrix} v_1 +
\begin{bmatrix}
j_1 <br />
j_2
\end{bmatrix} v_2
=
\begin{bmatrix}
i_1v_1 &amp; j_1v_2 <br />
i_2v_1 &amp; j_2v_2
\end{bmatrix}</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\$ \overrightarrow{v} \$ represented by the basis vectors (\$ \overrightarrow{i} \$, \$ \overrightarrow{j} \$) equals to the summation of the scalar multiple of \$ v_1 $\ with \$ \overrightarrow{i} $\ and the scalar multiple of \$ v_2 $\ with \$ \overrightarrow{j} $\.

More crudely, the linear transformation of \$ \overrightarrow{v} \$ shows us what \$ \overrightarrow{v} \$ in the "world" represented by the basis vectors in the coefficient matrix, looks like in our "world".</script>
